The [International Renewable Energy Agency](/International_Renewable_Energy_Agency) (IRENA) has meticulously reported that a total of 14,438 [megawatts](/Megawatt) (MW) of geothermal power capacity was operational worldwide by the close of 2020. This installed capacity collectively generated an impressive 94,949 [gigawatt-hours](/GWh) (GWh) of electricity during that year. ([35](/Geothermal_power#cite_note-35)) In theory, the Earth's geothermal resources are so vast they could easily meet humanity's entire energy demands. However, the cold, hard truth is that only a minuscule fraction of these global geothermal resources can currently be economically exploited on a [profitable](/Profit_(economics)) basis. ([36](/Geothermal_power#cite_note-36)) The planet has plenty to offer; we just haven't figured out how to politely ask for it, or rather, efficiently extract it, without breaking the bank or the ground beneath our feet.

[Al Gore](/Al_Gore), during his address at The Climate Project Asia Pacific Summit, famously suggested that Indonesia, with its extraordinary geological endowments, possesses the potential to become a true superpower in the realm of electricity production from geothermal energy. ([37](/Geothermal_power#cite_note-37)) This is hardly surprising, given its position on the highly active [Pacific Ring of Fire](/Pacific_Ring_of_Fire). Following this optimistic outlook, in 2013, the publicly owned [electricity sector in India](/Electricity_sector_in_India) announced an ambitious plan to develop the country's very first geothermal power facility. This pioneering project is slated for the landlocked [state](/States_and_union_territories_of_India) of [Chhattisgarh](/Chhattisgarh), marking a significant step for India into the geothermal landscape. ([38](/Geothermal_power#cite_note-38))

[Geothermal power in Canada](/Geothermal_power_in_Canada) also holds considerable promise, primarily due to its strategic location along the aforementioned [Pacific Ring of Fire](/Pacific_Ring_of_Fire). The region exhibiting the greatest potential within Canada is identified as the [Canadian Cordillera](/Canadian_Cordillera), a vast mountain range stretching from [British Columbia](/British_Columbia) all the way into the [Yukon](/Yukon) territory. Estimates for the generating output from this region have ranged widely, from a conservative 1,550 MW to a more optimistic 5,000 MW, underscoring the significant, yet largely untapped, resource. ([39](/Geothermal_power#cite_note-39))

The [geography of Japan](/Geography_of_Japan) is, by nature, exceptionally advantageous for geothermal power production. The archipelago is dotted with numerous [hot springs](/Hot_spring) and volcanic activity, which could readily supply the necessary heat for geothermal power plants. However, despite this natural abundance, a monumental investment in Japan's existing infrastructure would be absolutely essential to fully realize and exploit this potential on a large scale. ([40](/Geothermal_power#cite_note-40)) It seems even the most obvious solutions require significant upfront effort and capital.

